ces/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_imp_ver01/data/sn86086586/00414214812/1920123101/0226.pdf", "segment_count": 8, "url": "https://www.loc.gov/resource/sn86086586/1920-12-31/ed-1/", "word_coordinates": "https://tile.loc.gov/text-services/word-coordinates-service"}], "segment_id": "/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_imp_ver01/data/sn86086586/00414214812/1920123101/0226.xml", "segments": [{"access_restricted": false, "aka": ["http://www.loc.gov/resource/sn86086586/1920-12-31/ed-1/?sp=2"], "batch": ["whi_imp_ver01"], "campaigns": [], "composite_location": ["0/united states/", "1/united states/wisconsin/", "2/united states/wisconsin/rock/", "3/united states/wisconsin/rock/edgerton/"], "contributor": ["wisconsin historical society"], "date": "1920-12-31", "dates": ["1920-12-31"], "description": ["HURLEY SALOONS RAIDED BY DRYS Chicago Officers Arrest About Seventy Booze Sellers WETS UNABLE TO RESIST Town Is Taken by Surprise After a Wild Night o Prisoners Taken to Ashland Where Bonds Are Fixed by Commissioner Hurley Wis Dec 29Swooping down on Hurley the widest open town in the Iron range 48 armed federal prohibition agents from the office of Prohibition Agent Frank D Richardson of Chicago raided 38 of the 58 saloons arrested about 70 sa loonkeepers and others within an hour and seized thousands of dollars worth of moonshine and bonded liquors as evidence Working rapidly and quietly the agents caught the suspected law vio lators completely off their guard and effected their capture without blood shed The federal agents were armed but not a shot was fired during the opera tions The raid followed a wild night at Hurley during which liquor had been sold at bargain rates ranging from 35 cents for moonshine whisky to 75 cents for wellknown brands Among the arret ts were lumber jacks too paralyzed from liquor to real ize what was happening Taken by Surprise Reports had reached prohibition en forcement headquarters at Chicago that prohibition agents would be shot if"], "digitized": true, "e